    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shock Waves From the Mideast, on Two Fronts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher MacEvitt letter sees signs that Israels, as well as Palestinians, are not ready for peace</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Arafat's War,'' by Thomas L. Friedman (column, Oct. 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Arafat's War,'' by Thomas L. Friedman (column, Oct. 13):</p>
        <p>While I agree with Mr. Friedman's grim assessment, I think he ignores signs that the Israelis are also not ready for peace.</p>
        <p>The lynching of two Israeli soldiers in Ramallah was sickening. But what do the reports of Israeli Jews running through the streets of Nazareth shouting ''Death to Arabs!'' tell us about how ready Israelis are to accept peace?</p>
        <p>Let us not forget that it is not Israelis but Palestinians, often unarmed, who are being killed every day. Overtures of peace from the Israelis must include more than just words.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER MACEVITT  Princeton, N.J., Oct. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
